Here we see that for a debt of the city which is under an obligation to punish those of its subjects who have injured others, a certain in- corporeal right of the subjects is held bound, namely, their personal liberty3 so that they are enslaved till the city punishes the guilty. The Egyptians, as we learn from Diodorus, held that a man's body or liberty were not to be bound for a debt: but yet there is nothing in such a usage repugnant to nature: and the contrary practice has pre- vailed not only among the Greeks, but also other nations.
